 The `debounce` function in JavaScript delays the execution of a function for a certain amount of time after it has been called. This prevents the function from being repeatedly called by the user too quickly.

```javascript
function debounce(fn, delay) {
  let timeout;
  return function() {
    const context = this;
    const args = arguments;
    const later = () => {
      timeout = null;
      fn.apply(context, args);
    };
    if (timeout) { clearTimeout(timeout); }
    timeout = setTimeout(later, delay);
  };
}
```

Example usage:
```javascript
const fn = () => alert('This will not be called too quickly!');
const debouncedFn = debounce(fn, 200);
// call the debounced function as often as you want
debouncedFn();
```
